About
The Atomic Museum in Las Vegas, Nevada, documents the history of nuclear testing at the Nevada Test Site in the Mojave Desert about 65 miles northwest of Las Vegas.
Duration: 1-2 hours

    Great museum - fascinating subject
    I really enjoyed my visit. The exhibits are really well done. The coverage is surprising py in depth. I have learned about the Manhattan project elsewhere, but their coverage is first rate. The material you cant get anywhere else is the testing which is actually what was done near Las Vegas. This is also very well presented. The audio guide is OK but not great. There are plenty of audio-visual displays so you could really skip it. There are lots of related topics to learn about like waste&disposal, new efforts like NIF for non-explosion research. Good info about clean-up, too. I really enjoyed the info on nuclear rockets. Wow.

Looking for something to do in Vegas that will be different from anything else.
Aug 2024 Couples
WOW! What a great museum/learning experience. Excellent collection of artifacts from the early days of the Manhattan Project through today. The interactive exhibits are excellent and really give you an insight into the world of atomic/nuclear testing and weapons development. The way everything is explained and demonstrated, you don't have to be a rocket scientist to understand. It'll take you about 1.5 to 2 hours to go though if you look at all the exhibits, but its worth it. Highly recommend for couples and families with older childer (12+) not a lot for younger children to do.

138 contributions
I'm not Lisa, but my favorite thing is the Atomic Testing Museum on East Flamingo Rd. I am a history buff and it tells the story of the "Cold War" from 1951-1989. The State of Nevada contributed a lot to this effort by opening the Test Site where these horrific weapons were tested regularly and often. See a model 9 megaton bomb already to be loaded onto a B-52 to be "delivered". It's a tale all Americans should be aware of.
